<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-642-990  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 642 990.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 24 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mixed chip news in quarterly report. (semiconductor industry)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Endrijonas, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Semiconductor Equipment and Materials InternationalReportsSemiconductor industryIndustry AnalysisForecastingMarket Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MIXED CHIP NEWS IN QUARTERLY REPORT MOUNTAIN VIEW, CALIFORNIA, U.S.A., 1990MAY 22 (NB) -- Semiconductor Equipment and Materials International (SEMI) hasreleased its first report on industry trends, tracking shipments ofsemiconductor equipment as reported by SEMI members.andM;The data in the report represents more than 90 percent of all shipmentsworldwide.andP;  Plans call for the report to be released on a quarterly basis.andM;After three years of sustained growth, SEMI indicated that first quartershipments in 1990 declined by 11 percent.andP;  North American data, however,showed that orders exceeded shipments during both February and March.andM;Also shown in the report was that shipments of front-end manufacturingequipment decreased 12 percent in the first quarter of this year whencompared with the fourth quarter of 1989 while test equipment shipmentsdeclined 11 percent and assembly equipment shipments were off by fourpercent.andM;Thirty-four percent of semiconductor equipment in 1989 was shipped to USfactories with another 47 percent going to Japan.andP;  The rest of the worldaccounted for the remaining 19 percent.andP;  Total shipments were at an all timehigh in 1989 reaching $9.2 billion.andM;Also released by SEMI is the 1990 International Standards updated to includemore than 240 new specifications.andP;  The 1990 set consists of six books:chemicals, equipment automation/hardware, equipment automation/software,materials, micropatterning and packaging.andP;  According to Scott Young, SEMIstandards manager, the 1990 standards represent the efforts of more than3,000 volunteers from semiconductor manufacturers and their equipment andmaterials suppliers.andP;  The complete set is available for $200 while eachindividual volume sells for $75.andM;Two non-standards technical documents have been released by SEMI as well.andO;They are Facilities and Safety Guidelines and the 1990 Generic EquipmentModel (GEM), the latter containing the consensus requirements for automatedequipment control of eight companies: IBM, ATandamp;T, Intel, Motorola, NationalSemiconductor, Siemens, Texas Instruments and SEMATECH.andP;  Digital Equipment isexhibiting the first commercial implementation of the 1990 GEM at theSEMICON/West show in San Mateo, CA this week.andM;Facilities and Safety Guidelines is available for $75 while GEM sells for$40.andM;(Janet Endrijonas/19900523/Press Contact: Genevieve Young, SEMI,415-940-6936; Robert Schneider, Digital Equipment Corp., 508-496- 8844)</TEXT></DOC>